<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Great Ocean Road</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Great Ocean Road</h2><p><i>Victoria, Australia · B100, Torquay to Allansford</i></p><p><b>Built by 3,000 returned WWI soldiers as the world's largest war memorial — 243 km of Southern Ocean coast.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>192 km (119 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>1 long day; ideally 2–3 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Year-round; spring (Sept–Nov) and autumn (Mar–May) are quietest</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Tour buses on hairpins, koalas in road at Kennett River, no shoulders, summer crowds at Twelve Apostles</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>334</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Great Ocean Road was built between 1919 and 1932 by 3,000 returned soldiers as a memorial to comrades killed in WWI — making it the world's longest war memorial. The road clings to a coast where the Southern Ocean has been chewing on Miocene limestone for ten million years. The Twelve Apostles aren't twelve and never were (only ever nine, now seven after collapses), but standing on the boardwalk at sunset as the stacks turn orange is reason enough for the trip. Drive west — your lane is on the cliff side. Watch for koalas at Kennett River (look up, in the eucalypts) and southern right whales offshore June–September.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Split Point Lighthouse</b> — 1891 white tower above red cliffs at Aireys Inlet — the lighthouse from the children's TV series Round the Twist. Short headland walk.</li><li><b>Lorne</b> — Original beach resort of the Great Ocean Road. Erskine Falls 10 km inland; the Pier-to-Pub swim every January draws 4,000 entrants.</li><li><b>Kennett River</b> — Best chance of seeing wild koalas at close range — they sleep in the manna gums above the campground access road. Look up; they're slow.</li><li><b>Cape Otway</b> — Mainland Australia's oldest surviving lighthouse (1848). Whales and shipwrecks; the otway forest is full of giant tree ferns.</li><li><b>Twelve Apostles</b> — Limestone sea stacks 50 m high, eroding back at ~2 cm/year. Best at dawn or sunset. The Gibson Steps just east drop you to beach level beneath the cliffs.</li><li><b>Loch Ard Gorge</b> — Where the clipper Loch Ard wrecked in 1878, killing 52. Tom Pearce, 18, swam ashore with Eva Carmichael, 17, the only survivors. Walk the gorge floor.</li><li><b>Port Campbell</b> — Tiny former whaling town. The Razorback, Loch Ard, and London Arch (collapsed 1990, stranding two tourists) all within a few km.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
